<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the SIX `sys_choice` rows that
    enumerate the legal values of the `status` Choice field on the
    `x_[scope]_case` custom table inside the scoped application
    `x_[scope]_case_management`.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping verbatim):
        Field    Type     Constraints
        status   Choice   Draft, Open, In Progress, Pending, Resolved, Closed

    The values authored here are the EXHAUSTIVE, CLOSED enumeration that the
    AAP mandates - exactly six records, no more and no fewer. Per the
    MINIMAL CHANGE CLAUSE in AAP Section 0.7.2, additional statuses such as
    `Reopened`, `Cancelled`, `Suspended`, `On Hold`, etc. are explicitly out
    of scope.

    THIS IS THE MOST CROSS-REFERENCED CHOICE LIST IN THE ENTIRE SCOPED APP.
    Per AAP Sections 0.5.5 and 0.5.2, the labels declared here are read by:

      Two type-specific Flow Designer flows (OnUpdate filtered on status):
        ../flows/general_inquiry_state_machine.xml
        ../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml

      Five subflows that gate individual transitions:
        ../flows/sub_flows/validate_open_transition.xml      (Draft -> Open)
        ../flows/sub_flows/validate_inprogress_transition.xml (Open -> In Progress)
        ../flows/sub_flows/validate_pending_transition.xml    (In Progress -> Pending)
        ../flows/sub_flows/validate_resolved_transition.xml   (In Progress -> Resolved)
        ../flows/sub_flows/validate_closed_transition.xml     (Resolved -> Closed)

      Six business rules enforcing entity-level guards and side-effects:
        ../business_rules/x_[scope]_block_draft_backtransition.xml   (* -> Draft prohibited)
        ../business_rules/x_[scope]_block_terminal_closed.xml        (Closed -> * prohibited)
        ../business_rules/x_[scope]_set_opened_date.xml              (before-insert)
        ../business_rules/x_[scope]_set_closed_date.xml              (Resolved -> Closed)
        ../business_rules/x_[scope]_validate_assigned_agent_membership.xml
        ../business_rules/x_[scope]_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress.xml

      One Script Include exposing reusable transition guards used by both
      flows and business rules:
        ../script_includes/x_[scope]_CaseTransitionValidator.xml
        (canTransitionToOpen / ToInProgress / ToResolved / ToClosed)

      Two scripted REST endpoints serving the unauthenticated portal pages:
        ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_submit.xml
            (sets status='Draft' on insert; relies on the Title Case label
            declared by Record 1 below)
        ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup.xml
            (returns this field's stored value as one of the THREE whitelisted
            output fields per AAP Section 0.7.4: "the lookup page returns
            ONLY status, subject, opened_date - no internal fields exposed".
            The exact label string the anonymous external requester sees is
            the Title Case string defined here, e.g., 'In Progress'.)

      Three reports (one Agent Workspace, two Manager View widgets):
        ../reports/x_[scope]_my_open_cases.xml
            (filter: status NOT IN (Resolved, Closed))
        ../reports/x_[scope]_case_count_by_status.xml
            (donut grouped by status; six slices, one per label below)
        ../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_status.xml
            (bar grouped by status; six bars, one per label below)

      Ten synthetic demo cases satisfying AAP Section 0.4.1 minimum-data
      threshold ("at least one demo case in each of the six statuses"):
        ../seed-data/cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_01.xml ... _demo_10.xml

    THREE VERBATIM BLOCKING-ERROR MESSAGES from AAP Section 0.7.4 reference
    the labels declared below by Title Case string-equality comparisons:
        - "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case."
          (fires when a Resolved transition is attempted while any child task
           has status != Closed - compares against the label declared in
           Record 5 below and Record 3 of sys_choice_case_task_status.xml)
        - "Cases cannot be returned to Draft."
          (fires when ANY transition attempts to land in Draft - compares
           against the label declared in Record 1 below)
        - "Closed cases are terminal and cannot be modified."
          (fires when previous.status was Closed - compares against the
           label declared in Record 6 below)

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java line 141-142:
            @Column(name = "cm_case_status")
            private String status;
        ArkCase's `status` was a free-form `String` JPA column with NO
        platform-level enumeration check. Any caller could assign any
        arbitrary string. The legal values were scattered across constants
        files, the queue handler, and the state-change service - making it
        impossible to know the closed set without code archaeology. The
        ServiceNow target FIXES this by declaring a controlled vocabulary
        of EXACTLY six labels here, enforced at platform-validation time
        through the parent dictionary entry's `<choice>3</choice>` setting
        in ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_status.xml.
      - CaseFile.java line 307-316 contains the @PrePersist lifecycle hook:
            if (getStatus() == null || getStatus().trim().isEmpty())
                setStatus("DRAFT");
        defaulting null/empty to UPPERCASE "DRAFT". The ServiceNow target
        normalizes this to TITLE CASE `Draft` (Record 1 below). The default
        behavior is preserved at the platform level via the dictionary's
        <default_value>Draft</default_value> declaration; this Choice list
        merely enumerates the legal values, and Title Case is intentional
        per AAP Section 0.1.2 verbatim ("`case.status` default = `Draft`").
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFileConstants.java does
        NOT declare a status enumeration; it only declares OBJECT_TYPE,
        EVENT_TYPE_*, and queue-action constants. The status enumeration
        was therefore implicit / undocumented in ArkCase - the target
        FIXES that defect by declaring the six values here explicitly.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/ChangeCaseStatus.java line
        88-89 declares `private String status = "ACTIVE";` for the
        change-history entity - using values like "IN_APPROVAL", "DRAFT",
        "APPROVED" (all uppercase). These are reference-only and NOT
        replicated in the ServiceNow target. The history is captured by
        the platform's standard `sys_audit` table, enabled via the parent
        dictionary entry's <audit>true</audit> flag.
      - The ArkCase CaseFileQueueHandler also overrode status to "ACTIVE"
        on save, which has no analog here. The ServiceNow target uses
        `Open` (Record 2 below) for the equivalent post-Draft active state,
        deliberately renamed for clarity since "ACTIVE" was ambiguous in
        ArkCase (active in queue? active casework? active for retention?).

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - EXACTLY six records: no fewer, no more. Per AAP Section 0.5.7
        verbatim. The six records below are the COMPLETE enumeration.
      - Title Case labels: `Draft`, `Open`, `In Progress`, `Pending`,
        `Resolved`, `Closed`. NOT uppercase (ArkCase legacy), NOT
        lowercase, NOT camelCase. The agent prompt's "Most common error
        point" warning specifically calls out: `In Progress` is TWO words
        separated by a SINGLE ASCII space - NOT `InProgress`, NOT
        `In_Progress`, NOT `IN PROGRESS`.
      - Label = Value pattern: each `<value>` matches its sibling
        `<label>` byte-for-byte. The stored value IS the human-readable
        label - no integer state codes, no enum ordinals, no separate
        machine-key. This is a standard ServiceNow Choice-field idiom
        and matches the pattern used by sibling Choice lists in this app
        (sys_choice_case_type, sys_choice_case_priority, etc.).
      - Sequence ordering by lifecycle progression in increments of 100:
            Draft (100) -> Open (200) -> In Progress (300) -> Pending (400)
                -> Resolved (500) -> Closed (600)
        This matches the AAP Section 0.5.5 transition matrix's natural
        narrative arc and drives:
            (a) the dropdown order on the case form
            (b) the slice/bar order on the dashboard reports (donut + bar)
            (c) the lifecycle visualization intuition for end users
            (d) the future extensibility - increment-of-100 spacing leaves
                room for inserting new statuses without renumbering, though
                the AAP MINIMAL CHANGE CLAUSE prohibits adding any in this
                POC.
      - All six records are <inactive>false</inactive>: every value is
        active and selectable in the dropdown. There are no deprecated
        legacy values to filter out (this is a greenfield Choice list).
      - No <dependent_value/>: status is a TOP-LEVEL lifecycle indicator
        whose legal values do NOT depend on `type`, `priority`, or any
        other field. The flow-level transition guards enforce which
        VALUES are legal at runtime; the dependent_value mechanism is
        for declarative cascading at the form-rendering level only.
      - No <hint/>: the labels are self-documenting (Draft, Open, In
        Progress, Pending, Resolved, Closed are universally understood
        case-management terms). The agent prompt explicitly suppresses
        helper text per the POC scope.
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every record's `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` resolve into the `x_[scope]_case_management`
        scoped application by `source` attribute lookup. NO global-scope
        writes - the OOB tables sys_user, sys_user_group, sys_user_role,
        core_company, task, incident, etc. are never modified.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: the `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` text-node values resolve by scope source name
        (`x_[scope]_case_management`), not by literal sys_id. Each
        record's `<sys_id>` element value is THIS record's own
        deterministic primary key - computed as MD5 of the canonical
        identifier `x_[scope]_case.status.<Value>` so that re-generation
        of this XML yields byte-identical output (no random UUIDs). The
        sys_id is NOT a reference to any other record.
      - The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved per AAP convention;
        the PDI auto-assigns the actual scope id at App Engine Studio
        creation time, which the import process resolves into the final
        scope namespace.
      - English language only: `<language>en</language>` on every record
        per the POC scope. The platform supports localization via
        additional sys_choice records keyed by `language`, but no
        non-English locales are in scope.
      - `<sys_domain>global</sys_domain>` on every record: domain
        separation is not used by this scoped application.
      - No PII: the labels are categorical lifecycle terms only; no
        real names, email addresses, or organizational identifiers
        are derived from or stored in these records.

    Cross-references (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      THIS RECORD SET MUST LOAD AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml (scoped application)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml (scope record)
        - ../tables/x_[scope]_case.xml (parent table; status field's host)
        - ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_status.xml (parent dictionary entry;
          declares the column shape, choice=3, default_value=Draft, and
          audit=true. Without this entry the sys_choice records below
          have no column to attach to.)

      THIS RECORD SET MUST LOAD BEFORE all consumers enumerated above
      (flows, subflows, business rules, script includes, scripted REST
      endpoints, reports, and demo seed data). Loading order is enforced
      by the alphabetical Update Set preview ordering plus the
      record-by-record dependency-resolution pass.
-->
